This composition was a common feature in early cinema and drew inspiration from the theater and vaudeville/magic performances. A limitation of this approach is that characters typically move horizontally and do not approach or recede from the camera, as seen in Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), where actors enter from the right side and move back and forth along the horizontal axis.

The use of the frontal proscenium style also led to the prevalence of long shots and, occasionally, medium shots. Close-up shots were never used in any of the trick films from the Edison catalog, a practice borrowed from the theater and vaudeville, where the audience would view the entire performance within the confines of the stage. As was common in early cinema, actors rarely moved towards the camera, making close-ups virtually non-existent.

Most early trick films followed a pattern where a single conceptual shot equaled a film, limiting their length to around a minute or less, depending on the frame rate. This also restricted the narrative or dramatic potential of these films, which mainly featured short, vaudeville-style tricks, such as magic, disappearance, and switching acts with minimal storytelling. However, it's worth noting that in trick films, a single conceptual shot may consist of multiple physical shots combined to create an illusion of disappearance or appearance. A closer inspection of The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), an early trick film, reveals the moment when the physical shot containing Mary's severed head begins, even though the entire film is perceived as a single shot by the viewer.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early and passionate advocate for Republicanism, despite primarily being an agriculturalist. His profession and brief career in politics shaped him into a dedicated and outspoken individual who prioritized personal freedom and limited government. His strong connection to an agrarian system underpinned his views on government, as he sought to preserve and promote this perceived superior career path. This emphasis on his primary occupation colored his opinions on sovereignty, Constitutionality, and the judiciary.

Taylor believed that the United States had a unique opportunity to establish an ideal system, unencumbered by native traditions that might hinder its development. He firmly believed in the natural rights of individuals, which he saw as interconnected and essential. These rights should not be subject to government interference, as their denial would undermine the entire system. He argued that the concept of a "state of nature" often exploited the strong and cunning, but this was not an acceptable norm in a civilized society.

To create a perfect society, Taylor argued that the government must account for both the good and evil inherent in human nature. He rigidly adhered to a dualistic morality, asserting that government, being a human institution, would inevitably reflect both its virtues and vices. He believed that good principles, such as protecting private property, promoting agriculture, and discouraging excessive capitalism, would form the foundation of a fair government. This government would function equitably, irrespective of its administration, which would inevitably be driven by self-interest and avarice. However, self-interest was only considered a vice when it led to the exploitation of others. A well-designed government was necessary to manage humanity's natural flaws and prevent the introduction of bad principles.

Like many Republicans of his time, Taylor advocated for a strict interpretation of the Constitution, advocating for a limited federal government with powers explicitly stated in the document. He recognized that a broad federal government would be expensive and potentially tyrannical. However, he also believed that a literal interpretation without consideration for the Founding Fathers' intent could be misleading and prone to corruption. Furthermore, Taylor considered the Declaration of Independence the true charter of the United States, as it more clearly defined the country as a collection of sovereign states rather than a single nation.

Looking at Figure 17, we can see a significant drop in commuter log submissions during the third month of the project, which was somewhat concerning. The reasons behind this decline are unclear, but several factors might have contributed. At our New England campus, the onset of winter often results in fewer people commuting by bike or on foot. Additionally, the end of the fall semester in December means students and faculty are preoccupied with finishing schoolwork, processing grades, and other tasks, which may have pushed the commuter log to the backburner. Furthermore, December marks the start of the holiday season, leading to a month-long break for students and faculty, during which many don't need to come to campus. When classes resume in late January, the number of log submissions remained low, suggesting a possible connection. However, the numbers for February were even lower, leaving the reason for this decline unclear. It's possible that initial enthusiasm for the project naturally waned over time, which is a common phenomenon in such initiatives. To counteract this, we organized the Carpool Challenge Week in March, a special campaign to revitalize the project, which led to an increase in log submissions. 

One of the challenges we faced with this project is that people generally enjoy the freedom and flexibility of driving their cars, a deeply ingrained aspect of our culture. To encourage alternative commuting methods, we offered prizes in the form of gift cards to local businesses. While this was a successful strategy, it would have been interesting to see the impact of offering larger prizes, such as a new bicycle, hybrid car, or electric car. This could have helped sustain the project's momentum, particularly during the dip in engagement we experienced. The value of the prizes remained constant throughout the project, which may have contributed to the decline in participation. If the prizes had been increased over time, with the addition of more substantial rewards in December and January, it's likely that participation and engagement would have increased instead of decreased.

A security known as an exchange-traded fund (ETF) is designed to track an index, a commodity, or a collection of assets similar to an index fund, while being more flexible and traded like a stock on an exchange.  ETFs offer the diversification benefits of an index fund and the advantages of owning individual stocks, such as the ability to sell short, buy on margin, and purchase as few as one share per transaction.  Although these benefits are highly appealing, ETFs have significantly lower expense ratios compared to the average mutual fund.  However, there are some drawbacks, including the cost of paying a commission on any ETF trade, similar to paying for a stock order.  Additionally, ETFs offer a wide variety of funds to choose from.  It is essential for the astute financial investor to critically evaluate whether the stated benefits, such as diversification, are indeed present and to what extent they exist.  For the purposes of this analysis, we will be examining the ETF IHF and comparing it to its top 10 holdings to determine whether the benefits of owning a single ETF are comparable to those of a diversified portfolio of the same 10 stocks, as well as whether there are more optimal configurations of the same stocks that could provide a better risk-return ratio.

To make the evaluation manageable, we have decided to focus on the top 10 holdings, which account for 63.58% of the ETF's total assets.  Below are the top 10 holdings and their respective percentages of total assets.

To gauge how well these 10 stocks represent the ETF IHF as a whole, we can use the current percentage of assets, normalized to 100%, to estimate the contributions of each stock to a portfolio's Beta and Return if the portfolio consisted entirely of these 10 stocks in the same proportions as the ETF's holdings.  The calculations of Beta and Return are presented in the chart below.

From the data in the chart, it is clear that a portfolio consisting solely of the top 10 holdings would yield a 6.11% higher return than the ETF, representing a 16% increase in returns.  It is also evident that the Beta of the top 10 holdings is 0.12 lower than the ETF as a whole.  The results thus far suggest that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could offer higher returns with a lower risk.  Nevertheless, it is possible that the means of these two portfolios may not be statistically different from each other.

To determine whether these portfolios are statistically different, we have calculated the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and normalized it to 100% for comparison to the ETF IHF's accumulated standard deviation.

One of Edgar Allan Poe's notable poems is "Dream-Land," in which he prominently features the term "Thulé." Poe's use of this term can be linked to Virgil, who mentioned an island north of Britain as the edge of the known world. However, Poe's inspiration for Thulé may also have been influenced by German literature, which he was known to be interested in. 

A notable example of Poe's familiarity with German authors, including Goethe, can be seen in the similarity between their works. Karl J. Arndt notes the resemblance between "Poe's Politian" and Goethe's "Mignon," suggesting that Poe may have been drawing inspiration from Goethe. 

According to the Oxford Companion to English Literature, Goethe's work "Faust" is a celebrated poetic drama that was published in two parts in 1808 and 1832. Within the second part, there is a poem called "The King of Thulé," which tells the story of a king who is consumed by grief after the loss of his wife. This poem bears a striking resemblance to the character in Poe's "Dream-Land," with both featuring a sense of despair and a reliance on drinking to cope with emotional pain.

Interestingly, Goethe's "Faust" was adapted into a romantic drama by H.P. Grattan in 1842, just a year before Poe used the term Thulé in "The Pit and the Pendulum." Poe references Thulé twice in his collected works, using the phrase "ultma Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum" and incorporating it as a bookend in "Dream-Land." The parallels between "The King of Thulé" and "Dream-Land" suggest that they can be read as companion pieces, with both exploring themes of loss and loneliness. 

Given Poe's admiration for Tennyson and the widespread reproduction of Goethe's work, it is likely that Poe was familiar with Goethe's writing, which suggests that he may have drawn inspiration from "The King of Thulé" when creating his own "Dream-Land."

In California, if a customer suffered an injury after slipping and falling on an applesauce spill in a grocery store, they may be eligible for punitive damages if the store manager acted with malicious intent. A court is unlikely to immediately dismiss Jennifer Palmer's claim for punitive damages. To justify an award of punitive damages, a plaintiff must provide evidence that the defendant's actions were taken with a reckless disregard for the potential harm that could result from their behavior, as well as that the conduct itself was despicable. Palmer will be able to argue that Martin should have anticipated the potential harm of not cleaning the spill, given that multiple customers had previously slipped and fallen in the store in the months leading up to her accident. She will also argue that Martin's failure to have the spill cleaned, despite being aware of the potential risks, demonstrates a willful and conscious disregard for customer safety. While Palmer's argument that Martin's actions were despicable is not as strong, it is still a reasonable claim, especially considering that six slip-and-fall incidents occurred in 2009 and Martin failed to take adequate measures to ensure store safety. 

On October 13th, 2009, at 5:00 pm, an employee of D&D Markets, Rich Wayne, informed his manager, Paul Martin, about an applesauce spill in an aisle. Martin responded by stating he was on dinner break and unavailable to deal with customer complaints. Fifteen minutes later, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also notified Martin of the spill, and he gave the same response. At 5:30 pm, Jennifer Palmer slipped and fell on the spill, suffering a serious back injury. Prior to Palmer's accident, there had been five reported slip-and-fall incidents at D&D's in 2009. Palmer is now suing D&D for compensatory and punitive damages related to her injury, and we are considering whether to file a motion for partial summary judgment on the punitive damage claim. 

In California law, a plaintiff can recover punitive damages for a breach of an obligation not based on a contract if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud, or malice." California Civil Code section 3294(a) defines malice as conduct that was intended to cause harm, or, in the absence of intent, conduct that is "despicable" and committed with a "willful and conscious disregard of the rights or safety of others." Courts have characterized conduct as malicious when it was committed with a deliberate disregard of the plaintiff's rights when the defendant was aware of the potential dangerous consequences of their actions and deliberately failed to avoid those consequences, as seen in the case of Taylor v. Superior Court of Los Angeles County, 598 P.2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

It has been almost four years since I took a course in Islam at CBC, where one of the most debated topics was whether Islam is inherently hostile. In my opinion, this question remains highly relevant today, particularly when considering the shift in mass media's perception of Islam and extremists since 9/11.  What's striking is the transformation from a hostile view to an extreme level of tolerance for Islam in America. This shift is exemplified by the fact that in 2001, it would have been unimaginable to have a presidential candidate like Barack Obama, who has a clear Muslim background in his family.

The biography of the Prophet Muhammad fascinates me. Contrary to my previous understanding of his history, the biography depicts him as a humble martyr rather than a conqueror who forced conversions to Islam. According to my initial knowledge, Muhammad was known to conquer and assimilate tribes, forcing them to adopt Islam. However, the biography portrays him as a leader who was often misunderstood, and his humility eventually won over those who came to understand his message.

I've also noticed eerie similarities between the ministries of Jesus and the miracles attributed to Muhammad. One notable example is when Muhammad miraculously multiplied mutton and milk to feed a large group of people. This narrative style suggests that the authors aimed to present Muhammad as a humble prophet who didn't need to prove himself but lived a life of truth and miracles. This approach downplays the significance of Jesus' life and ministry, almost as if they're borrowing and attempting to supplant the essence of Jesus' personhood with Muhammad's story.

The biography also contains numerous accounts that appear to be intended to provide evidence of the 'witness' or 'conversion' of individuals to Islam. However, many of these stories are presented from a third-party perspective, which undermines their credibility. The stories often originate from hearsay, making it seem suspicious and diminishing their impact.

What bothers me most about this work is the attempt to portray Muhammad as a godly, humble, wise, and gentle figure. However, historical records contradict this image of Muhammad, leading me to wonder if Muslims today are aware of the true circumstances surrounding his rise to power.

The core teachings of Jesus and the ideals he promoted during his lifetime were initially overlooked as Christianity evolved beyond his era.  When examining the history of Christianity, we observe a pattern where the faith has gradually strayed further away from its roots.  Today, society is witnessing an increasing awareness and a progressive shift towards a more refined understanding.  While traditionalists continue to hold onto their conventional views and resist any departure from established teachings, their influence may not be substantial enough to dictate the broader direction.  As the years pass, a growing awareness of historical context among Christians will emerge, sparking a desire to distinguish between the original intent of Jesus' teachings and the additional doctrines that were incorporated over time.  This process may take centuries, but it is inevitable that Christianity will eventually undergo a significant reversal, returning to its original form.  As this trend spreads across the United States and Europe, it will inspire a movement to strip away the layers of doctrine, gradually stripping back to the essence of Jesus' message, as it was presented before other thinkers and interpretations took hold.  When this shift affects the masses in these regions, the church as an institution will still maintain its strength, guiding the way forward.  As a result of this reversal, the extreme diversity within Christianity will give way to increased uniformity of belief and practice.  The distinctions between regions, denominations, and other divisions will be replaced by growing similarities.  History is replete with examples of reversals, such as the Roman Empire's shift from persecution to Christian dominance, or the transformation of the United States from African-American slavery to African-American leadership.  The impending reversal in Christianity will unfold in a similar manner, as the faith seeks to reclaim its roots and, in the process, reduces diversity.  It is essential to note that a key factor in making this reversal possible will be the adoption of a more metaphorical interpretation of Jesus' words, rather than viewing them as literal statements of fact.  To understand the trajectory of Christianity, it is necessary to look back to its origins in Judaism, which was the theological foundation of the Christian faith.  By examining the period before the Roman Empire's control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E., we find that Judaism was characterized by a rich diversity of perspectives, with the Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and ordinary people each holding distinct views.

The Jungle highlights the inherent self-centered nature of human beings. At their core, people prioritize their own interests over others and seek to improve their lives at the expense of those around them. This is exemplified in the factory owners and managers of Packingtown, who are only driven by the desire to expand their businesses and accumulate wealth, disregarding the impact on the environment and those affected by their operations. Upton Sinclair vividly illustrates this in his description of the factories: "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." This image serves as a stark representation of the devastating consequences of their actions, such as pollution and environmental degradation. The owners and managers display a callous disregard for the well-being of their employees, using them as mere means to an end. They exploit their workers, pushing them to work excessively long hours and laying them off without warning or support, all in pursuit of profit. During the time period depicted in the novel, there were few laws or regulations protecting workers' safety and well-being, allowing the factory owners and managers to operate with impunity. The workers in Packingtown were expected to endure deplorable working conditions and treatment, with no access to information or assistance. Although some unions formed to represent the workers, they often profited from their struggles, making the situation even more dire. The workers were described as being in a state of servitude, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Many authors employ various techniques to evoke specific feelings or attitudes in their readers towards essential subjects. Some of these methods are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald utilizes a range of these techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. He frequently employs an uncommon combination of adjectives and nouns to create a distinct atmosphere surrounding a subject. Alternatively, he assigns meaning to a symbol and later utilizes it to achieve a particular effect. In The Great Gatsby, Fitzgerald develops and utilizes the meaning of several colors, including gold, green, white, and red/pink, to convey specific emotions and ideas.

Fitzgerald creates associations for colors such as white/gray and red/pink, and then leverages these meanings to create a particular impression of an object. The meaning he assigns to white/gray is uniformity, with white representing a more refined and upper-class atmosphere, while gray implies something older and faded. To establish this meaning, Fitzgerald consistently uses both colors in the novel's beginning. White is repeatedly associated with characters such as Daisy and Jordan, who are often depicted wearing white. For instance, Nick wears "white flannels" to Gatsby's party, and Tom wears a "white shirt" when meeting Myrtle. Fitzgerald reinforces this connection by describing mundane, unimportant subjects with these colors, such as the "white chasms of lower New York" and the "gray names" on Nick's timetable.

Fitzgerald further develops this meaning by applying these colors to common or unremarkable people and places. He describes Jordan and Daisy's past as a "white girlhood," and the "gray cars" and "gray land" in the valley of ashes. The dog-seller is portrayed as a "gray old man." After establishing these associations, Fitzgerald uses white/gray to signify a sense of uniformity or lack of importance. This technique is first employed when describing Daisy. After a period of limited use of these colors, Fitzgerald reintroduces Daisy dressed in white, which contributes to her characterization as a uniform, interchangeable entity, something Gatsby desires but also longs for. He repeats this technique to reinforce this impression, using images such as a "gray haze of Daisy's fur collar" and her appearance in a "white" dress before Tom and Gatsby's encounter.

San Diego County boasts significant agricultural output, primarily due to its favorable climate characterized by mild temperatures and ample sunlight. The region's agricultural sector includes a wide variety of crops such as tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a substantial demand for locally sourced, organic produce in the area, with many community-supported agriculture initiatives having lengthy waiting lists for their products. Organic dairy and poultry products are also in high demand. Many local farms provide opportunities for visitors to explore their operations, as well as engage in recreational activities like hiking and birdwatching. By adopting organic farming practices, landowners can take advantage of government incentives while enhancing biodiversity, creating opportunities for ecotourism, and generating revenue through educational programs.

In addition to catering to a potentially lucrative market niche, organic farming often leads to increased biodiversity in the area due to the absence of chemical usage. However, organic farming can be more labor-intensive and costly than conventional methods, particularly when it comes to pest control and soil fertilization. Additionally, small organic farms often lack the efficiency and economies of scale enjoyed by larger operations. Other conservation practices, unrelated to organic farming, can also incur higher labor costs, including the use of cover crops, strategic grazing rotation, invasive species removal, and active management of plant growth to create specific habitats.

A hypothetical landowner in this scenario might seek financial assistance or expert guidance to optimize both profit and habitat quality. 

The hypothetical land in question is located adjacent to the town of Potrero in unincorporated San Diego County, California, and spans 160 acres of chaparral, non-native grasslands, and oak woodlands, situated next to the Cleveland National Forest. This area falls within the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan, which currently considers over a hundred plant and animal species, many of which are endangered or threatened with listing, including the Stephens' kangaroo rat, mountain yellow-legged frog, several butterfly species, and the California gnatcatcher.

Historically, this region was inhabited by Native Americans for centuries before being settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 19th century. The land in question was part of an original homestead patent, likely used for grazing and/or wood production over the intervening decades.

To provide a realistic example of a farming operation in this area, I selected a piece of property from a real estate website and researched available government programs to determine the options available to small-scale farmers for reducing costs and preserving wildlife-friendly practices. I also identified an organic farm in the same region as a model for what a landowner might aim to achieve.

In negotiations, understanding and accounting for cultural differences is crucial. Culture encompasses a wide range of nuances that cannot be defined by a single characteristic or trait. Stereotypes, such as "Russians are stubborn" or "Japanese are accommodating," oversimplify the complexities of a culture and are often inaccurate. A more effective approach is to comprehend the specific cultural values and attitudes relevant to the negotiation at hand, as they can significantly impact the dynamic at the bargaining table. When interacting with a foreign culture, one tends to draw comparisons to their own, which can lead to misunderstandings.

To navigate cultural differences, it is essential to delve into the culture, its history, and values, rather than judging or trying to alter them. Acceptance and understanding of the culture, particularly when dealing with a weaker bargaining position, can facilitate a smoother negotiation. When on unfamiliar territory, respecting local customs and traditions can help break down cultural barriers and facilitate progress.

It is essential to recognize that culture extends beyond national or international boundaries. Companies within a nation develop their unique corporate cultures, shaped by factors such as work hours, communication styles, hiring practices, and dress codes. These differences can be observed within a single nation, as seen in the varying corporate cultures across the United States. The apparent uniformity of certain cultures can be misleading, and it is crucial to look beyond the surface to uncover the complexities.

Understanding a culture's values is particularly vital, as they provide insight into the underlying motivations and priorities. For instance, in cultures where saving face or communal harmony is valued, a negotiator will avoid publicly embarrassing their company or superior. On the other hand, in cultures that prioritize a hard-driven bargain, negotiators may be more likely to push for a favorable deal. Considering these cultural factors beforehand can significantly enhance the effectiveness of a negotiation. Nevertheless, gaining a deeper understanding of one's counterpart on a personal level can also be invaluable in achieving a successful negotiation.

The famous phrase "The fool has said in his heart, 'There is no God,'" originates in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible and is at the forefront of St. Anselm's argument for God's existence. This notion is also shared by Thomas Aquinas. Since both authors defend the same concept, it's essential to assume they are correct in their belief in the God of the Bible for the sake of comparison. If we were to consider a deity that differs from the one in whom our authors believe, we wouldn't be able to properly compare their arguments, as they are fundamentally centered around a specific idea of God. 

While each author presents valid points, neither provides a comprehensive foundation for believing in God. To demonstrate this, let's first examine St. Anselm's argument. Anselm's reasoning relies on gaining understanding through faith, exploring one's own consciousness to find proof of God. He suggests that God's existence is inherent within our understanding, making it impossible to conceive of his nonexistence. Although the specifics of Anselm's argument can be wordy and confusing, the core idea is that the proof for God lies within our minds and doesn't necessitate any external evidence. This concept of accepting something without definitive empirical proof is often referred to as faith in Christian texts.

In contrast, Thomas Aquinas proposes that God's existence can be proven solely through reason and empirical evidence, eliminating the need for faith altogether. This approach would be advantageous in evangelism, a crucial aspect of Christianity, as it would enable the recruitment of new followers without relying on their willingness to accept something that cannot be proven. Instead, Aquinas employs logical arguments based on change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony to demonstrate the logical necessity of God's existence. He illustrates that understanding the characteristics of a missing puzzle piece is possible through the assembly of the rest of the puzzle, even if the piece itself is not visible.

It is believed that around the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince destined to be known as the Buddha was born. Throughout his life, he renounced worldly life and achieved enlightenment, which led to the establishment of Buddhism, specifically the Theravada tradition. Although the religion is now over 2,500 years old, it has undergone significant changes, as seen in countries like Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is observed. This event, attended by both monks and laypeople, holds spiritual significance, despite the Buddha never mentioning a similar celebration. These changes can be observed in both the surface-level customs and the core teachings of Buddhism. The Theravada Buddhist community has adapted its core principles over time, influenced by both internal and external forces, which may be either hostile or benevolent.

To facilitate this discussion, it is essential to understand the concepts of internal and external forces. An internal force refers to influences stemming from within the Buddhist community, regardless of the individual's monastic status, whereas an external force originates from non-Buddhists. A hostile force is any influence that damages or seeks to damage the Buddhist community, often driven by a negative perception of Buddhism. In contrast, a benign force does not intend to harm or help the community but may inadvertently cause either outcome. These terms will be used throughout this analysis.

To begin, it is crucial to explore the fundamental principles of Theravada Buddhism. Adherents seek refuge in the triple gem of the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma, encompassing the Tripitaka, consists of three baskets of Buddhist scriptures: the Sutta Pitaka, containing the teachings; the Vinaya Pitaka, outlining disciplinary rules; and the Abhidhamma Pitaka, delving into metaphysical concepts. These concepts include the notions of Anatta (no permanent self), Dukkha (inherent suffering), and Anicca (impermanence). Recognizing these principles is essential to escaping Sansara, the cycle of birth and death, and ultimately overcoming the afflictions of lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion), which are characteristic of a state of enlightenment. The Vinaya Pitaka sets forth guidelines for Buddhist adherents, with laypeople adhering to five precepts and monks following a more extensive set of disciplinary rules. The four noble truths are the fundamental teachings of Buddhism: the acknowledgment of Dukkha (suffering is inherent in life), the causal relationship between attachment and suffering, and the possibility of overcoming suffering.

The United States and Mexico provide a notable example of two nations that were embroiled in a prolonged rivalry spanning 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. This rivalry peaked during the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, in which the United States defeated Mexico and secured control over Texas and the American Southwest as new territories. Over the course of their relationship, the two nations experienced numerous conflicts, which gradually subsided before the onset of World War I. The initial tensions arose from fundamental differences in their values, cultural practices, and traditions, as well as conflicting material interests. 

Similarities can be drawn with other countries that share a border, as these nations often experience clashes of interests, leading to the development of rival positions. The United States and Mexico's relationship is not unique in this regard, with David M. Pletcher commenting that "only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-standing American diplomatic challenges" (Pletcher, 1977, p. 41). Their geographical proximity to the United States, in addition to historical rivalries, contributed to their tumultuous relationship. In contrast, many other Latin American nations have maintained positive relations with the United States.

The discord between the two nations was also fueled by differences in their religious beliefs, which have been a source of conflict in many nations throughout history. Sally Frahm noted that Americans' opposition to Catholicism and monarchy in the 18th and 19th centuries was a significant factor in their relationship with Mexico (Frahm, 2001, p. 86). This ideological divide mirrored the rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union during the Cold War, which was characterized by a mix of ideological and interest-driven competition. However, the United States and Mexico's rivalry was rooted in their differing religious preferences, rather than their political systems. The animosity between the two nations was, in part, inherited from the distrust between their former colonial rulers, the English and Spanish, which hindered the establishment of amicable diplomatic relations.

According to Diehl and Goerts (2000), 17 disputes arose between Mexico and the United States during the 57-year rivalry period. Most of these disputes involved territorial issues, such as Mexican raids into U.S. territory and border problems. The presence of bandits and outlaws from American border towns posed a significant challenge, which was eventually addressed through joint military action by both nations (Schmitt, 1974, p. 97). 

Schmitt (1974) explained that the rivalry began to subside as Mexico became increasingly reliant on the United States and, eventually, as American ambitions shifted from territorial expansion to economic intervention in Mexico, marking the end of the rivalry in the late 19th century.

It has been fifteen years since I was unexpectedly disabled by an illness that I was unaware of. At the time, I was a nurse, a profession I chose to pursue in response to the uncertainty and insecurity I experienced during my childhood. The notion that one could always find work because people would inevitably fall ill was a mantra that resonated with me. Although my true aspirations lay in becoming a scientist or journalist, I opted for nursing as a more stable career path.

However, I found myself at a crossroads at the age of 46, with no savings and no ability to work. Fifteen years of living on Social Security Disability have left me with nothing to call my own. Each day is a struggle, and I face challenges to my sense of security, safety, and self-esteem. One thing that I am certain of is that without the support of my family and a few close friends, I would not have been able to survive these years, regardless of my strength. In reality, when adversity strikes, one's sense of strength is often greatly diminished.

My point is that life is inherently unpredictable, and emergencies – big or small – will inevitably arise. No amount of preparation can guarantee a smooth ride, and some challenges are too overwhelming to face alone.

While I agree that Americans should not rely too heavily on big government, I believe that fostering a culture of mutual trust and assistance would be a more desirable approach. Rather than relying solely on individual efforts to prepare for disasters, I advocate for Americans to learn from one another, to offer help when needed, and to ask for help without hesitation. This approach is reminiscent of the values that truly sustained our ancestors during difficult times – compassion, mutual respect, and the sharing of resources.

The idea of rugged individualism, touted by some Conservatives as a driving force behind the country's success, is a myth. In reality, it was our forefathers' ability to come together, show compassion, and share resources that helped them overcome hardships. The pioneers who traversed the Rockies in wagon trains did not achieve their goal in isolation; it was through collective effort and support.

I, too, believe in being prepared for emergencies. I have a disaster kit, first aid supplies, and other essential items to ensure my safety in case of a crisis. If possible, having a small farm with a wood stove and the ability to preserve food can be a great asset. However, this is not a substitute for building a support network of neighbors who can offer aid when needed. Therefore, it is essential to get to know those around you and build relationships that can provide a sense of security and community in times of need.

The question of why organisms evolve in a particular manner remains a topic of interest, and it is unclear if there are any restrictions or constraints that influence the direction of evolutionary change.  Even in the early 20th century, D'Arcy Thompson noted that biologists were still struggling to mathematically describe even the simplest organic forms.  However, more recently, researchers have applied mathematical modeling to the development and evolution of mollusk skeletons, covering both their development from birth (ontogeny) and their evolutionary history (phylogeny). Our study aims to investigate how combining mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic changes in Prunum with experimental studies can help reveal the underlying mechanisms driving the direction and magnitude of evolutionary developmental changes. By analyzing X-radiographic images of Prunum species, we identified quantitative parameters that can be used to model both hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies. These parameters were fed into the software program CerioShell to simulate various shell morphologies that could be used to interpret the boundaries of possible morphological change in Prunum. We are integrating these findings with experimental and descriptive studies to gain a better understanding of major evolutionary events in this group.

A shell can be thought of as a tube that travels through space over time, making 360-degree turns as it grows. These turns, known as whorls, are thought to spiral around an imaginary central axis called the columella, which runs through the shell's central column. The rate at which the whorls expand can vary, and a continuous line separating each whorl is referred to as a suture. In most shells, the largest whorl (the body whorl) is the last one formed. The spire consists of all the whorls except the last one. The apex is the tip of the spire, while the opposite end is the base. The animal exits its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be viewed from various angles, including apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural perspectives. The typical orientation of a shell is an apertural view, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing upwards.

To count the whorls, the shell should first be viewed from the apical perspective, and then the first suture should be identified. A line can be drawn to divide the shell into two parts, and whorls are counted from this line, estimating them to a quarter of a whorl if necessary.

A shell can be seen as a series of openings that move through time and space as the animal grows and builds its shell. It is possible to track the path of the aperture by measuring the coordinates of the center of each whorl's opening, as well as its horizontal and vertical radius. This trajectory can be graphically and mathematically represented. By developing a mathematical formulation, it becomes possible to modify parameters and alter the mollusk's skeletogenesis.

Despite a decade of relative stagnation in neonatal and infant mortality rates in Indonesia, the country still has a long way to go to meet its Millennium Development Goals, particularly in child and maternal health.  Although progress has been made in several areas, such as water and sanitation, the country's health system struggles to make significant improvements in these areas.  This points to a need to strengthen the overall health system rather than focusing solely on targeted programs.

Indonesia has made some progress in increasing the number of skilled healthcare workers attending births, with 72% of births now meeting this standard.  However, this statistic includes traditional birth attendants who may not have the necessary medical training to handle complications, contributing to a high number of maternal deaths due to hemorrhage.  Thus, these improvements may be misleading, and more work is needed.  Additionally, the percentage of children under five treated by a healthcare professional for diarrheal illnesses has decreased, and data on postnatal care is incomplete, revealing concerns in these areas. 

The low cesarean-section rate of 4% indicates a lack of access to specialized medical care, with a significant disparity between urban and rural areas.  In urban settings, the c-section rate is 7%, while it is only 2% in rural areas, highlighting the disparity in access to healthcare services.  Furthermore, a 27% gap in service utilization exists between the poorest and richest quintiles, indicating that the poor face significant barriers in accessing healthcare due to out-of-pocket costs.

When considering ways to improve neonatal and maternal care indicators, the key question is how to effectively address the shortage of healthcare services.  The main issue is whether Indonesia should focus on developing targeted programs or strengthening its overall health system, rather than solely addressing pre and post-pregnancy care.  While program-specific approaches may yield faster results and have more manageable objectives, they also have drawbacks.  Investing heavily in one area of the health sector can divert resources and personnel away from other areas, leading to duplication of services and inefficiencies.  This can result in unnecessary administrative burdens and waste of resources.

Victorian novels are characterized by their meticulous attention to detail and focus on the aristocracy of the time period. However, novels such as Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights diverge from this tradition. These two works incorporate an element of mystery and a distinct flair for the unusual, characteristics not typically found in novels of the era. This emphasis on the unknown strengthens the characters within the narrative, offering a deeper understanding of their motivations and emotions.

In the midst of turmoil, a character's mind becomes flooded with a multitude of confusing ideas and images. As seen in the passage from Dickens, a character's perception of reality becomes distorted, with fragmented scenes unfolding before their eyes. This disorienting experience is characterized by the blending of reality and fantasy, leaving the character with an intense sense of unease and discomfort.

In Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, the authors frequently employ dream sequences or dream-like states to convey the inner workings of the characters' minds. These surreal episodes often reveal the characters' deepest fears, insecurities, and desires. For instance, Oliver Twist's hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit serve as a manifestation of his inner turmoil and desperation. When Oliver relives the shooting scene in chapter 28, he is overwhelmed by a sense of helplessness and despair, highlighting his lack of control over the events unfolding around him. This portrayal underscores the theme of Oliver's powerlessness, as he is unable to influence the outcome of events, even when his life is at stake.

Furthermore, the recurring theme of defeat and hopelessness is a significant aspect of Oliver's character development. His inability to take control of his circumstances, despite being faced with dire consequences, suggests that he has become resigned to his fate, allowing Fagin's influence to shape his actions and reactions.

In the same vein, the passage from Dickens continues to convey the theme of despair and hopelessness. The protagonist's perception of time becomes distorted, with days passing by in an instant, while the nights seem interminably long and filled with a sense of foreboding. The contrast between the fleeting nature of time and the eternal duration of the protagonist's suffering serves to heighten the sense of hopelessness and desperation.

About two years ago, I was working in an after-school program where I tutored elementary school students in various subjects. I focused on helping them with their struggles in English and reading, as these were my areas of expertise. However, I was approached by one of the instructors to work with a third or fourth-grader named Adrian, who was facing significant difficulties with reading. As I worked with him, I realized that something was amiss; he had a peculiar reading problem, where he could effortlessly pronounce some letters, but struggled with others. This was quite unusual, especially considering that Adrian's mother spoke only Spanish, yet he spoke flawless English. It wasn't until I met his mother that the issue became clear: Adrian could read, but he had a weak understanding of the English alphabet. Although I'm not sure if this realization significantly impacted his reading abilities, I hope he has made progress since then.

I share this anecdote to highlight the issue of language barriers in schools, particularly in California. My story also serves to illustrate that this problem may not always be as apparent as we assume, even for students who speak perfect English, reading can still be a significant challenge. The situation with Adrian's mother made me realize that the solution to this issue is not as straightforward as it seems. While a simple approach like tutoring in English reading, focusing on the alphabet and pronunciation, might work for some, it is not a universal solution for students whose first language is not English.

In my opinion, the key to addressing this complex issue lies in combining multiple strategies. The dual language system, mainstream immersion, private tutors, and ESL classes, among others, are not mutually exclusive and can be used in conjunction with one another. In fact, combining these approaches can lead to better outcomes.

The dual language system, for instance, has been shown to be highly effective, not only for children whose first language is Spanish, but for all children. Research indicates that students in two-way bilingual education programs outperform their peers academically. Despite the common misconception that this approach is a waste of resources, studies have shown that it benefits the majority of students, not just a select few. If we were to adopt this approach as a standard rather than an exception, all students would reap the benefits. However, implementing this system would require some adjustments, such as providing bilingual support staff, rather than expecting all teachers to be fluent in multiple languages. This would not only be impractical but also unrealistic. Nevertheless, I believe that having bilingual support staff or tutors can make a significant difference in helping students overcome language barriers.

As children, many of us are taught that there exists something beyond our comprehension, something greater than ourselves.  This concept can be learned in various settings, such as Sunday school or through personal reflection.  While some people adhere to the faith passed down to them by their families, others refuse to accept any notion of a higher power, instead embracing a self-centered worldview.  It is common for individuals to adopt one set of values, only to later change and adopt another.  Our pursuit of spirituality serves as a means to understand ourselves and our place in the world.  We seek guidance, a beacon of hope, to lead us out of darkness and into the light.

In a moment of quiet contemplation on our front porch, my father shared with me his favorite type of bird, the cardinal, while the sound of rain pounded against the tin roof above us.  His frail appearance, brought on by recent health struggles, was a stark contrast to his former robust self.  As he gazed out into the rain, I felt a deep sense of unease and a longing to talk to him about my impending loss, but I knew that acknowledging it would only make the reality more painful for both of us.  I found solace in our shared silence, and I drew closer to him, sitting beside him as we both looked out into the rain.

My father's passing occurred five days after my twenty-second birthday in December.  Despite the medical treatments that prolonged his life beyond the expected period, his suffering persisted.  I found myself questioning a higher power, wondering if it existed at all and, if so, whether it had abandoned me.  In the stillness of night, I chose not to pray, as I felt that any divine being had long since stopped listening to my pleas.

I had not wanted to witness his transition from life to death, so I chose not to be there.  I couldn't bear to see the person who had given me life slipping away.  Instead, I chose to remember him through his life, not his passing.  I knew him better than anyone, and I believed that he would not have wanted me to be present at his death.  I spent three days in solitude, waiting for news of his passing.  Unfortunately, I was not even contacted during that time.

The term "Gothic Novel" is itself an oxymoron, as described by Ian Watt in The Rise of the Gothic Novel, combining the concepts of "old" and "new." The Gothic genre has been subject to diverse opinions, ranging from criticism for lacking depth to praise for evoking a sense of the "terrible sublime." The pioneering work, Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, drew upon both ancient and modern romance elements to establish the proto-Gothic genre and create a new style of literary expression. By blending old theatrical elements with the modern novel's format, Walpole presented "A Gothic Story" that appealed to a unique blend of past and present.

The Gothic genre heavily draws from medieval theatre, architecture, and traditions, which were already perceived as archaic and unsophisticated in comparison to modern societal and literary advancements at the time of The Castle of Otranto's publication. However, it was the combination of the dramatic, theatrical aspects of the Gothic with the novel's ability to offer a personal insight into character psychology that allowed the genre to endure and become both timeless and innovative to readers separated from the original writing by time.

One of the key features of Gothic literature is the romanticization of the concept of Chivalry. In The Castle of Otranto, the medieval idea of chivalry, which involves the training of a noble knight, is both preserved and transformed. This theme holds significant importance in Gothic literature because it represents the idealized image of a brave, honorable, and capable knight, and the perceived lack of such qualities in the authors' contemporary society. By employing chivalric concepts and ideals, the Gothic past is idealized and romanticized, foreshadowing the evolution of Gothic into Romantic literature. 

The author, Horace Walpole, wrote The Castle of Otranto during a time of social turmoil, and his writing reflects his concerns about the apparent decline of moral values and innate goodness in society. This is evident in the character of Frederic, a prince who embodies many chivalric traits. The description of Frederic as a prince who has suffered, been affected by tragedy, and is said to have been killed by infidels, exemplifies the exaggerated image of the gallant and courteous knight that is characteristic of the Gothic genre.

Supply chain management is the intricate network of processes involved in moving goods from the initial customer order to the final delivery of products to customers. The concept of supply chain management was first introduced by Keith Oliver in 1982, a renowned consultant who outlined the essential components of effective supply chain management, encompassing planning, implementation, and control to meet customer needs efficiently. The core elements of a supply chain include production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information, which business managers utilize to deliver exceptional customer service.

Production is the foundation of the supply chain process, requiring careful planning of 'when', 'why', 'where', and 'how' products will be manufactured. To achieve this, managers need to understand customer requirements, which can be determined by analyzing market trends. This analysis enables managers to decide on the products to be produced, their quantities, production locations, and optimal production volume to meet customer demands. Scheduling workloads and maintaining equipment are critical tasks to be addressed during this stage, as every detail plays a vital role in the overall efficiency of the process. A well-planned production process, like the ones adopted by companies such as Wal-Mart and Target, ensures a smooth operation, minimizing confusion and miscommunication.

Supply is another crucial element in supply chain management, involving strategic decisions that define a company's core capabilities and outsourcing partnerships. This may involve allocating different production divisions to specific tasks, leveraging their unique equipment, workers, and specialties. Alternatively, management may opt to outsource certain processes to other companies to achieve velocity, which means providing quality products while maintaining low costs by enhancing flexibility and efficiency.

The sign on the street corner, held up by Ellen Page, reads, "Hitler is alive in Burma." The juxtaposition of this message with the image of the actress, who starred in the film Juno, is striking. Burma, now known as Myanmar, is a country in Southeast Asia that has been ruled by a repressive military regime since a coup in 1962. In 2007, a wave of protests swept the country, known as the "Saffron Revolution," which was led by Buddhist monks who wore saffron-colored robes. The protests, which began peacefully, soon turned violent as the government cracked down on the monks and their supporters. Journalists, including a Japanese photojournalist named Kenji Nagai, were arrested and killed while covering the protests. Estimates of the death toll vary, but one colonel who defected from the military claimed that the true number of deaths was in the thousands. 

This is not an isolated incident. Throughout history, governments have sought to suppress dissent and maintain control over their citizens. Ancient Roman emperors claimed divine authority, while Japanese emperors were believed to be gods. Even in modern times, leaders have used various means to silence opposition, including the 1989 Tiananmen Square protests in China, the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, and the atrocities committed during Hitler's "Third Reich." These examples highlight the enduring pattern of governments using force to maintain power and silence dissent.

Duke Ellington's enduring impact on jazz is largely due to his remarkable career longevity and his ability to showcase his orchestra's individual talents through his creative genius. Although his piano presence is often understated in many compositions, Ellington excelled as a composer, crafting intricate and complex pieces that highlighted the unique abilities of each band member. As a master composer, he skillfully created frameworks that allowed soloists to improvise freely while writing tightly orchestrated pieces that emphasized the distinctive styles of individual members. This approach not only showcased the orchestra's cohesive sound but also enabled Ellington to produce some of the most groundbreaking pieces in the history of jazz.

The Grove Music dictionary highlights Ellington's innovative use of voice as a musical instrument throughout his career, exemplified by Creole Love Call, an early piece that incorporated vocals to add texture and depth without lyrics. This 12-bar blues piece demonstrates Ellington's ability to complement the styles of his soloists, a trait evident throughout his work. The composition features six distinct choruses, each showcasing a unique aspect of the band's sound:

The first chorus features a call-and-response dialogue between voice and reeds, with the voice transitioning from smooth to rough. The second chorus features a muted trumpet solo elaborating on the melody and emphasizing extended blue notes. The third chorus features a sweeping clarinet solo in a high register accompanied by a subtle syncopated piano phrase. The fourth chorus is a full-band rendition of the first chorus, with a call-and-response between brass and reed sections. The fifth chorus is the climactic point of the piece, with reeds taking the lead and syncopated stop-time from the brass and rhythm sections. The final chorus returns to the first chorus's structure, with the voice adopting a growl technique and soloing as an instrument. The piece concludes with a brief tag featuring a vocal run and a dissonant novelty ending by a trombone.

Ellington's use of voice as a tone-color instrument is a recurring theme throughout his work, as seen in pieces like Creole Love Call. In Hot and Bothered, recorded a year later, Ellington combines his orchestration skills with his sensitivity to tone color, using a call-and-response phrase between Bubber Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing to create a rich and complementary sound. In It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing), Ellington leverages Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton's talents as a trombonist to great effect, introducing the melody on muted trombone.

She had long harbored an unfulfilled longing, a sense of emptiness that persisted since her early teenage years. By the time she turned 17, she had become convinced that the solution lay in finding a romantic partner, yet she found herself uninterested in the boys who had shown interest in her. Her introspection had led to various theories, but none had seemed satisfactory. Her life was a continuous cycle of questioning her desires.

Ordinarily, her home was a peaceful haven, with her parents maintaining a calm atmosphere, and disagreements with her being a rare occurrence. Her parents valued her independence and lively personality, which complemented their own tranquil nature. However, today was an exception. As she searched for inspiration, she was startled by her mother's anguished cry from the kitchen. She rushed in to find her mother lying on the ground, in obvious pain, and repeatedly saying "Ow." With growing panic, her daughter rushed to her side and offered assistance. "Ouch... sweetie, I need you to take me to the hospital," her mother gasped. The daughter quickly assessed the situation and helped her mother get into the car.

Upon arriving at the hospital, the daughter was surrounded by the harsh smells of disinfectant and illness mixed with an air of concern. But her focus remained on her mother's well-being. She quickly helped her mother onto a rolling bed and called for medical assistance. The doctors and nurses rushed to her side, and her daughter was left to anxiously wait. 

It turned out that her mother had slipped off a step stool while trying to retrieve a vase from a high cabinet.

This study aimed to identify a connection between adherence to the Mediterranean Diet, reflected by a high alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score, and a reduced risk of heart disease and stroke, as well as stroke-related mortality. The aMed diet, an adaptation of the traditional Mediterranean diet, emphasizes the consumption of plant-based foods, including fruits, nuts, whole grains, legumes, and plant-based proteins (excluding potatoes), along with higher intakes of monounsaturated fats and fish, while limiting animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol consumption is also permitted.

Previous studies had found an inverse link between adherence to the Mediterranean diet and total and cardiovascular mortality. Furthermore, a clinical trial demonstrated that the Mediterranean diet was more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and improving the cholesterol ratio in obese individuals. However, prior research did not specifically examine the relationship between the Mediterranean diet and stroke or stroke mortality.

This observational study tracked 74,886 middle-aged women without a history of cardiovascular disease or diabetes, who were participants in a larger cohort study of 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. An aMed diet score was computed from self-reported food frequency questionnaires (FFQs) six times between 1984 and 2004, assessing nutrient intake over the preceding year. Over 95% of nurses maintained their participation throughout the 20-year study period. The accuracy of FFQs was validated, and reports of heart disease, fatal heart disease, and stroke were confirmed through medical records, hospital records, or death certificates. Cases where records were unavailable were classified as "probable" and included in the analysis, with approximately 17% of all strokes and 24% of non-fatal heart attacks falling into this category. Additional factors, including body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and hormone replacement therapy, were also calculated for each FFQ. Starting in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was also assessed.

To account for individual variations and better represent long-term dietary habits, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging scores from two prior years). Potential confounding factors were adjusted for, including age, smoking, body mass index, menopausal status, hormone replacement therapy use, multivitamin intake, alcohol consumption, physical activity, and aspirin use.

The study employed Cox proportional-hazard modeling to investigate the association between the aMed score and the risk of heart disease and stroke, using separate models for fatal and non-fatal heart disease and stroke types.

The findings showed that greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, indicated by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of heart disease and stroke in women. Over the 20-year follow-up period, 2391 cases of heart disease, 1763 cases of stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal heart disease and strokes combined) were identified. Women in the highest aMed quintile had a lower risk of both heart disease and stroke compared to those in the lowest quintile (relative risk, 0.71).

The United States faced a severe financial crisis in 2007, marked by soaring unemployment, a collapsed housing market, and numerous prominent corporations on the brink of collapse. This ongoing economic downturn has prompted the question: what led to this crisis, and how can we prevent it? In essence, the financial crisis was triggered by shortsighted and reckless policy decisions that forced banks and companies to issue high-risk sub-prime loans to an underdeveloped financial system. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, tasked with underwriting and repackaging these mortgages into complex financial instruments, further exacerbated the problem. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks struggled to maintain their capital reserves, leading to a chain reaction that spread financial chaos throughout the economy.

The roots of the crisis date back to 1999, when the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions in a bid to boost the President's popularity. This decision laid the groundwork for the sub-prime crisis that unfolded seven years later. In 1999, New York Times journalist Steven Holmes sounded a warning about the potential consequences of this policy: Fannie Mae, the largest mortgage underwriter in the country, faced pressure from the government to expand its lending to low- and moderate-income households, and from shareholders to maintain its profit margins. Holmes foresaw the possibility of a government bailout similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.

A combination of factors contributed to the economic turmoil, including the proliferation of complex mortgage products such as adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs). These instruments deeply entangled various sectors of the economy with the housing market, leaving households and financial institutions heavily exposed to even minor fluctuations in housing prices. As a result, the housing market bubble burst, leaving financial institutions that had invested in mortgage-backed securities reeling. In 2007, the top five U.S. investment banks collectively held $4.1 trillion in mortgage debt, equivalent to approximately 30% of the country's GDP. The crisis ultimately led to the sale of Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch at fire-sale prices, the dismantling of Lehman Brothers, and the forced transformation of Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley into commercial banks subject to strict regulation. Fannie and Freddie, burdened with $5 trillion in mortgage debt, were placed under government control in September 2008.

The infamous exposition - a part of storytelling where writers often struggle to strike the right balance between drawing readers in and overwhelming them with unnecessary details.  It's the moment when you spread your creative wings, only to risk sending your audience to sleep or reaching for the "Back" button.  Even the most seasoned writers like Dr. Merlin have been known to get frustrated when faced with Too Much Information, much to the dismay of their monitors.

Exposition is a nemesis for many writers, reminding them to include background information to progress the plot, but it can easily become a hindrance if not done correctly.  This is where the age-old 'show, don't tell' rule comes into play, yet even experienced writers like Dr. Merlin often find themselves slipping into lengthy passages that fail to engage.

In essence, exposition is about providing the reader with essential details through straightforward narration.  It's similar to a character dumping a wealth of information on another character in a film, as seen in 'The Rime of the Ancient Mariner'.  When authors do it in literature, it can be a problem, especially when used to convey the history of a character or event.

A prime example of this can be seen in literature.  You're reading a story and learn about the heroine meeting her beloved at a specific time and place, their wedding being grand, and her husband's tragic demise.  If the author spent two pages detailing this sequence, with the couple only exchanging two lines of dialogue, it would likely be unengaging.  Instead, the author should delve deeper into the husband's character, showcasing his love through his words and actions, allowing the reader to experience his presence in the heroine's life.  This in turn would make the reader more emotionally invested in the story and better understand the heroine's character.

In short, the reader needs meat to complement the story's bare bones - 'They met, they married, he died.'  As a writer, it's crucial to provide this depth, even when it's tempting to rush through certain aspects of the narrative.  This is especially true when introducing new characters, such as a former Air Force member who's now running a gas station, with a complex past and secretly ambitious dreams.  It's essential to avoid overwhelming the reader with too much information and instead, present it in a way that adds to the story, rather than detracting from it.

I watched two news broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio, on August 13, 2011. The first one was a live NBC 4 newscast. The lead story centered around a man in Ashley, Ohio, named Shad Hostettler, who had stabbed his wife multiple times. Although the wife's name was not disclosed, police had already arrested Hostettler. The news team allocated approximately two minutes to this story, which seemed reasonable given the developing nature of the case.

The subsequent story reported on an 18-year-old named Travis Buyers, who had been critically injured in a shooting in the Sharon Woods area. At the time, no arrests had been made, and the SWAT Team was conducting an investigation. This story appeared to be brief, which may have been due to the fact that the victim was a member of a minority group. It is a common observation that such incidents involving minorities may receive less media attention. 

The following story involved a gunshot hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter, which was likely caused by a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle. A $5000 reward was being offered to anyone who could provide information leading to the arrest of the perpetrator.

The weather forecast for the weekend predicted rain and thunderstorms for Saturday afternoon, with temperatures ranging from the mid to low eighties. Although the segment was a bit short, it was presented as a teaser to encourage viewers to tune in for further updates.

The newscast also covered a robbery at a UDF in Clime Road, Columbus, where a dark-skinned black man wearing a hoodie had stolen from the store. He was described as being approximately six feet tall and weighing about 150 pounds. It was notable that the news team devoted a considerable amount of time to emphasizing the perpetrator's ethnicity.

Another story featured Rene Rodriguez, a convicted Texas-based drug kingpin. He had been found guilty of smuggling large quantities of marijuana from Texas to Ohio. One peculiar aspect of this report was the use of the phrase "300 months" instead of "25 years" to describe his prison sentence. The inclusion of Rodriguez's Hispanic ethnicity in the story might have been unnecessary.

There's a profound and unbreakable connection between brothers, encompassing a complex array of emotions, including love, pride, jealousy, and even cruelty. This unique bond allows brothers to understand each other on a deep level, often seeing themselves reflected in their sibling. When faced with challenging situations, the true nature of this bond is revealed, whether it's characterized by positivity or negativity. Along with these emotions comes a sense of responsibility, as one must confront the consequences that arise from them. Gazing into a brother's eyes, one sees not only their own reflection but also their true character, which is revealed through their actions and the outcomes of those actions. This theme is explored in "The Scarlet Ibis," where two brothers navigate the intense feelings associated with their bond amidst a vividly described backdrop. As they embark on a futile journey, bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in a climactic scene, and only one brother manages to survive. The novel conveys this theme through the direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and his interactions with his brother, as well as the narrator's perspective, which conveys the complex emotions experienced by the protagonist and his perception of the world around him.

The protagonist's actions are driven by a single dominant emotion: pride. From their initial outing together to their final, fateful excursion, he harbors resentment towards Doodle. The protagonist had envisioned a brother who could learn from him and share in his adventures, such as holding his breath, running, or climbing vines in Old Woman Swamp. However, Doodle's physical limitations, resulting from a weak heart, render this ideal impossible. The protagonist's dreams are crushed when he realizes that Doodle will unlikely participate in these activities. In fact, he even experiences anger towards the child, as evidenced by his thoughts of suffocating him with a pillow. However, the child's smile brings about a change in him, revealing an underlying love for his sibling. This shows that his conviction was likely not strong, and his instincts as a brother still prevailed.

The human brain is a complex and imaginative information processing system that has been described using a variety of metaphors as technology progressed. Initially, it was compared to a simple wax tablet, then to a piece of papyrus, followed by a book, and most recently, to a computer. It is essential to keep in mind that these metaphors are limited in their usefulness and may lead to misconceptions. 

The process of processing information in the brain begins with sensory organs converting physical stimuli, such as touch, temperature, sound waves, or light, into electrical signals. These sensory inputs are repeatedly transformed by the brain's algorithms through bottom-up and top-down processing. For instance, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, the brain initially breaks down the information into basic components like color, orientation, and the borders of the object. This allows it to determine that the image represents a box. However, top-down processing builds upon these initial conclusions to speed up the recognition process by using previously made decisions. This can help identify the object as a specific box, rather than a hole in the background.

Once information has been processed to a certain point, an attention filter decides its significance and determines which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, even though the brain processes every blade of grass when looking at shoes, a healthy attention filter ensures that we don't notice individual blades. On the other hand, we might focus on our name being spoken in a noisy room. There are multiple stages of processing, and the results are repeatedly modulated by attention.

In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are different types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term memory. The process starts with encoding, where information is converted into a form that can be stored. Various types of encoding exist for different types of sensory inputs. For example, verbal input can be encoded based on how it looks, how it sounds, or what it means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Research on animals suggests that working memory, which stores information for around 20 seconds, is sustained by an electrical signal that temporarily loops through a series of neurons. Long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained through the structure of specific types of proteins.

There are numerous models explaining how knowledge is organized in the brain, based on various approaches such as human memory retrieval, computer science, and neurophysiology. The semantic network model proposes that concepts are represented by nodes, which are linked based on their relatedness. For instance, in this model, "chair" might be linked to "table," which could be linked to "wooden," and so on.

In his dystopian novel Brave New World, Aldous Huxley critiques the impending dangers of unchecked technological advancement and the capitalistic framework that sustains it. The society in the novel prioritizes communal harmony over individuality, conditioning its citizens from birth to pursue instant gratification above all else. This results in people being reduced to mere pawns in a larger game, confined to a single ideology dictated by the World Controller. Upon analyzing the novel through the lens of Marxist ideology, it becomes evident that Huxley harbors suspicions about the development of these systems. The presence of Marxist terminology such as homogeny and reification underscores the notion that Brave New World is a commentary on the shortcomings of the emerging economic systems of Huxley's time.

Huxley satirizes capitalism by employing the concept of false consciousness, a Marxist thesis which suggests that the common citizenry is kept in the dark about their true relationships with other economic classes, prioritizing personal gain instead. This is achieved through the ideological control of the proletariat and common laborers, which is exemplified in the conditioning of the people in Brave New World. The lower classes, represented by Delta and Gamma, lack genuine autonomy, with their drive to consume and indulge strengthened through hypnopædia. This manipulation is orchestrated by the World Controller. The novel also illustrates the concept of hegemony, where a dominant group exercises control over others, in this case, the upper classes. The lower classes are oblivious to this manipulation, blindly embracing an ideology that perpetuates the existing structure. In contrast, the upper classes, such as Alphas and Betas, are aware of the manipulation but choose to accept their position, with few exceptions. The interactions between social classes in the novel serve as a testament to the perceived oppression of capitalism.

The novel portrays relationships between individuals as superficial, with characters lacking depth and distinction, even among major characters. Huxley may be suggesting that the rise of technology and capitalism erodes human free will and self-expression. Love and extreme emotions are nonexistent, replaced by shallow interactions that focus on physical appearances and superficial connections. The societal classes' complacency with their positions in the hierarchy and their absolute obedience to their role in the community reflect the Marxist concept of the proletariat, who are led to believe they are superior as long as they conform and consume.

I have been enrolled in University Park for approximately two and a half years, with four and a half semesters under my belt. For many students, including myself, navigating the campus can be a significant challenge. During my freshman year, I resided in an East Halls dorm, situated on the easternmost part of campus, excluding the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center.
